An aggressive mucoepidermoid carcinoma that arises from the breast. It is characterized by the presence of focal necrosis and high mitotic activity. Lymph node and distant metastases are common. The prognosis is usually poor.
Removal of anal tissue, for microscopic examination.
Removal of tissue from the pancreas for microscopic examination.
Grafting or transplanting cells, tissues, or organs between genetically non-identical individuals.
Removal of myocardial tissue for microscopic examination, usually taken from the right heart using a transvenous approach.
Removal of tissue from the liver for microscopic examination, using a needle.

Removal of tissue from the liver for microscopic examination.
Removal of tissue from the colon for microscopic examination, using an endoscope.
Surgical removal of the tonsils.

A slow growing mucoepidermoid carcinoma that arises from the breast. It is characterized by the presence of keratinization in the neoplastic squamous cells and lumina formation by glandular neoplastic cells. Complete excision may be curative.
Surgery involving removal of a wedge-shaped portion of the tongue.
Surgical removal of the gallbladder,using a laparoscope.
A procedure to remove dead tissue or foreign material from a wound to expose underlying healthy tissue and to promote healing.
Removal of tissue from the duodenum for microscopic examination, using an endoscope.
Surgical removal of the tonsils and adenoids.
Removal of tissue from the stomach for microscopic examination, using an endoscope.
Removal of tissue from the esophagus for microscopic examination, using an endoscope.
Surgical removal of the vermiform appendix.
Complete or partial removal of a polypoid lesion from the mucosal surface of the large intestine.

A neoplasm that arises from the breast and is composed of cells exhibiting neuroendocrine differentiation. It is classified as neuroendocrine carcinoma or neuroendocrine tumor G1 and neuroendocrine tumor G2. Most cases are neuroendocrine carcinomas.  Primary neuroendocrine tumors in the breast are very rare.
Surgical removal of a triangular wedge shaped section of tissue.
Surgical reconstruction or replacement of all or part of a malformed, diseased, degenerated, or otherwise damaged joint.
Removal of a portion of skin tissue, for microscopic examination.
Removal of rectal tissue, for microscopic examination.
Removal of tissue from the prostate for microscopic examination, using a needle.
Surgical removal of all of the uterus, via an abdominal approach.
A surgical procedure in which an individual's native liver is removed and replaced by a donor liver.
Surgical removal of the pharyngeal tonsils (adenoids).
Removal of tissue from the breast for microscopic examination.
Removal of tissue from the kidney, for microscopic examination.

A synthetic guanine derivative with antiviral activity.  As the active metabolite of ganciclovir, ganciclovir-5-triphosphate (ganciclovir-TP) appears to inhibit viral DNA synthesis by competitive inhibition of viral DNA polymerases and incorporation into viral DNA, resulting in eventual termination of viral DNA elongation.
A well-differentiated, low grade neuroendocrine neoplasm arising from the breast.
